# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1906-chicago-white-sox-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The **1900 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1900.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 14, with the Brooklyn Superbas as the regular season champion of the National League.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas and runner-up Pittsburgh Pirates competed in the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, over four days, with Game 1 on October 15 and ended with Game 4 on October 18.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas defeated the Pirates in the best-of-five series in four games.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the return of a postseason championship series (albeit as a one-off), the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, following the end of the Temple Cup in 1897.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the aftermath of the National League contracting from 12 to 8 teams, eliminating the Baltimore Orioles, Cleveland Spiders, Louisville Colonels, and Washington Senators.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The elimination of major-league baseball from these cities prompted the minor league American League to declare themselves as a major league the following year.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 schedule consisted of 140 games for the eight teams of the National League.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring all eight teams.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season on October 14.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, took place between October 15 and October 18.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1902 Chicago White Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Sox had a record of 74–60, finishing in fourth place in the American League.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1902 Philadelphia Athletics season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team finished first in the American League with a record of 83 wins and 53 losses.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] In 1902, the Philadelphia Phillies obtained an injunction, effective only in Pennsylvania, barring Athletics' second baseman Nap Lajoie from playing baseball for any team other than the Phillies.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Lajoie had played for the Athletics in 1901, and appeared in just one game in 1902 before the injunction went into effect.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The American League responded by transferring Lajoie's contract to the Cleveland Bronchos, who were subsequently known as the "Naps" in Lajoie's honor for several seasons.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] Following the A's pennant winning season, the *Philadelphia Inquirer* organized a championship parade for the team through the city on Monday night, September 30, 1902.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] The team proceeded in open carriages and were reviewed by Philadelphia Mayor Ashbridge in front of the *Inquirer'*s building on Market Street.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] "There were more than 25,000 base ball enthusiasts from Philadelphia and nearly every town within a radius of twenty miles of the city in the parade.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] A thousand effigies of the "white elephant" were carried by the paraders.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-philadelphia-athletics-season] There were fifteen bands and twenty fife and drum corps in line to furnish music for the marchers." It was estimated that more than 200,000 turned out for the parade.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The **1903 Boston Americans season** was the third season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 91 wins and 47 losses, 14+1⁄2 games ahead of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston went on to participate in the first World Series held between the AL and National League (NL) champions.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans won the 1903 World Series in eight games over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Macon, Georgia.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Cy Young was a coach for the Mercer University baseball team, also based in Macon.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Boston Americans played an exhibition game against Mercer University (with Cy Young pitching for Mercer) on March 23; the outcome being a 13─2 victory for Boston.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest losing streak was three games, which occurred twice; April 20–23 and September 22–23.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team's longest game was 12 innings, which occurred three times.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 13 home runs and had 104 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .331 batting average.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] It was Freeman's third consecutive season with at least 100 RBIs.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 40 appearances (35 starts) and pitched 34 complete games with a 28–9 record and 2.08 ERA, while striking out 176 in 341+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (21–13) and Tom Hughes (20–7).
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; July 31 at Washington, August 29 at Washington, and September 25 vs.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] Boston had an 11-game winning streak from May 28 through June 8, to put themselves in the AL lead.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] While they briefly fell into second place in mid-June, behind Philadelphia, Boston then won 9-of-10 to recapture the lead, which they held through the end of the season.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The Americans met the Pittsburgh Pirates in the first modern World Series, an agreement between the AL and the NL as a post-season tournament.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1903-boston-americans-season] The "Amerks" won the best-of-nine series in eight games; after falling behind, 3–1, they won four games in a row, clinching the championship at their home field, the Huntington Avenue Grounds, in Boston.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The **1904 Boston Americans season** was the fourth season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished first in the American League (AL) with a record of 95 wins and 59 losses, 1+1⁄2 games ahead of the New York Highlanders.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The Americans were set to play the National League (NL) champion New York Giants in the 1904 World Series; however, the Giants refused to play.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 7 home runs and had 84 RBIs, and Freddy Parent with a .291 batting average.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 43 appearances (41 starts) and pitched 40 complete games with a 26–16 record and 1.97 ERA, while striking out 200 in 380 innings.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The team had two other 20-game winners; Bill Dinneen (23–14) and Jesse Tannehill (21–11).
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] The team had three games end in a tie; September 13 at Philadelphia, September 14 vs.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] Both ties against New York were the second games of doubleheaders.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1904-boston-americans-season] Note: Stats in brackets are derived from Retrosheet which differ from the stats found on MLB.com.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The 1906 season was the seventh season overall for the Chicago White Sox, and their sixth season in the major leagues.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The Sox won their second American League pennant and their first World Series championship.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The Sox won 93 games in the regular season–– a plateau they would not reach again until the 1915 season–– to claim the pennant, propelled by a historic 19-game winning streak in August.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] They won the league pennant largely on the strength of their pitching staff, as their team batting average of .230 was the worst in the AL.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The 1906 White Sox team became known as the *Hitless Wonders*, having won the American League pennant despite posting the lowest team batting average (.230) in the league.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The team had been in fourth place by the end of July, 7½ games behind the defending champion Philadelphia Athletics, when they went on a 19-game winning streak that drove them into first place.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] No American League team would beat the 19-game winning streak for almost 100 years.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The team made up for their lack of hitting prowess by leading the league in walks, hit batsmen and sacrifice hits.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The White Sox pitching staff had a league-leading 32 shutouts and the second lowest earned run average in the league.
[src:1906-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The White Sox then defeated their cross-town rivals, the heavily favored Chicago Cubs in the 1906 World Series.
